"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","content":"Process lists of API, filesystem, or subprocess work without unbounded parallelism."},"374":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#refresh-several-repositories","content":"Refresh several repositories"},"375":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"Why this is friendlier"},"376":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#good-variation-stream-the-input","content":"Good variation: stream the input"},"377":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#avoid-unbounded-fan-out","content":"Avoid: unbounded fan-out"},"378":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","content":"This recipe is for the common \"do this for every item\" path: refresh every repo, fetch every avatar, resize every image, or inspect every file. The work is independent, but starting it all at once can make a user's machine or an upstream service miserable."},"379":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","content":"Use `mapLimit()` when you want tuple errors, shared cancellation, stable output order, and a hard ceiling on active work."},"380":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"Output order matches `repositories`, so UI code does not need to sort the result back into place."},"381":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"The first tuple error aborts in-flight work and stops starting new items."},"382":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"A parent `AbortSignal` can cancel the whole batch when the user navigates away."},"383":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#why-this-is-friendlier","content":"`concurrency` is explicit, so expensive work stays polite by default."},"384":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#good-variation-stream-the-input","content":"If repositories come from an async source, use `yieldless/iterable` instead of building a large array first."},"385":{"id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/bounded-batch-work#avoid-unbounded-fan-out","content":"That can launch dozens or hundreds of subprocesses. Use `mapLimit()` or `mapAsyncLimit()` so the user’s machine stays responsive."},"386":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","type":"page","content":"Checkout Flow","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow"},"387":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","content":"A customer checkout example with validation, inventory reads, payment resilience, rate limits, and receipt jobs."},"388":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"The moving parts"},"389":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#checkout-service","content":"Checkout service"},"390":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#receipt-worker","content":"Receipt worker"},"391":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#why-this-is-a-good-fit","content":"Why this is a good fit"},"392":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#avoid-hiding-business-rules-behind-a-generic-pipeline","content":"Avoid: hiding business rules behind a generic pipeline"},"393":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","content":"Checkout is a good Yieldless fit because it crosses several failure-heavy boundaries without needing a framework runtime: user input, inventory reads, payment APIs, rate limits, and background receipts."},"394":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","content":"This recipe keeps those boundaries explicit. The service code still reads like ordinary TypeScript, but the painful edges return tuples and accept cancellation."},"395":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/router` turns the tuple service into an HTTP response"},"396":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/schema` validates checkout input"},"397":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/cache` and `yieldless/batcher` keep inventory reads efficient"},"398":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/limiter` protects a payment API quota"},"399":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/breaker` fails fast while the payment provider is unhealthy"},"400":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-13","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/queue` stores receipt work for a local worker"},"401":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-14","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/fetch` keeps remote API calls in tuple form"},"402":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-15","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#why-this-is-a-good-fit","content":"Cart validation returns a normal HTTP validation response."},"403":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-16","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#why-this-is-a-good-fit","content":"Inventory reads batch together and cache briefly, which helps busy product pages."},"404":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-17","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#why-this-is-a-good-fit","content":"Payment quota is explicit before the payment call."},"405":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-18","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#why-this-is-a-good-fit","content":"The circuit breaker stops a payment outage from becoming a retry storm."},"406":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-19","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#why-this-is-a-good-fit","content":"Receipt delivery is queued so checkout can finish without waiting on email."},"407":{"id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow-20","page_id":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/checkout-flow#avoid-hiding-business-rules-behind-a-generic-pipeline","content":"That hides the parts reviewers most need to see: stock checks, idempotency, payment error handling, and what happens after the customer pays."},"408":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","type":"page","content":"Command Runner","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner"},"409":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","content":"Run local tools with live logs, deadlines, output limits, cancellation, and safe argument boundaries."},"410":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner#command-runner-service","content":"Command runner service"},"411":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner#showing-progress-in-a-ui","content":"Showing progress in a UI"},"412":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner#returning-a-useful-result","content":"Returning a useful result"},"413":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner#good","content":"Good"},"414":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner#avoid","content":"Avoid"},"415":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","content":"Many products eventually need to run a local tool: a project build, a formatter, a video transcode, a document converter, or a test command. The hard part is rarely starting the process. The hard part is keeping the UI responsive, stopping cleanly when the user cancels, and returning enough detail to explain what happened."},"416":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","content":"This recipe builds a small command runner for developer tools and desktop apps."},"417":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner#command-runner-service","content":"`runScript()` accepts the script name as an argument, so Node keeps argument boundaries intact. `runTrustedPipeline()` uses a shell command string because the `&&` syntax is intentionally shell-specific and controlled by the application."},"418":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner#showing-progress-in-a-ui","content":"The UI does not need to know how the process is spawned. It subscribes to ordinary events and owns cancellation through one `AbortController`."},"419":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner#returning-a-useful-result","content":"The command result includes the command, args, working directory, duration, stdout, stderr, exit code, and signal. That makes audit logs and support screens possible without reparsing the terminal transcript."},"420":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner#good","content":"Use `runCommandSafe(file, args)` when any part of the command came from a user, a project setting, or a database row."},"421":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner#good","content":"Use `runShellCommandSafe()` for trusted shell syntax that is easier to read as one command."},"422":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-13","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner#avoid","content":"Do not put user-controlled values into a shell command string."},"423":{"id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner-14","page_id":"/docs/recipes/command-runner","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/command-runner#avoid","content":"Use separate arguments instead. It reads a little longer, but it avoids shell injection and quoting edge cases."},"424":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","type":"page","content":"Customer Import","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import"},"425":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","content":"Import a customer CSV with validation, bounded concurrency, duplicate checks, progress events, and polite API calls."},"426":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import#import-service","content":"Import service"},"427":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import#streaming-progress-to-a-ui","content":"Streaming progress to a UI"},"428":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import#why-this-is-a-good-fit","content":"Why this is a good fit"},"429":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import#avoid-one-promise-per-row","content":"Avoid: one promise per row"},"430":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","content":"Bulk imports are familiar to almost every product team. They look simple until a customer uploads a file with thousands of rows, duplicate emails, invalid data, and a slow CRM integration."},"431":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","content":"This recipe keeps the import understandable:"},"432":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","content":"validate each row as data"},"433":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","content":"check duplicates in batches"},"434":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","content":"limit outbound CRM calls"},"435":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","content":"publish progress as rows complete"},"436":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","content":"stop cleanly when the user cancels"},"437":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import#streaming-progress-to-a-ui","content":"The UI does not need to know about batching, rate limiting, or CRM failures. It gets ordinary domain events."},"438":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-13","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import#why-this-is-a-good-fit","content":"Invalid rows become skipped rows instead of crashing the whole import."},"439":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-14","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import#why-this-is-a-good-fit","content":"Duplicate checks batch together instead of hitting the database once per row."},"440":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-15","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import#why-this-is-a-good-fit","content":"CRM calls run with bounded concurrency and a rate limit."},"441":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-16","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import#why-this-is-a-good-fit","content":"A single `AbortSignal` lets the user cancel the import from the UI."},"442":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-17","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import#why-this-is-a-good-fit","content":"Progress is an async subscription, so it works for web sockets, server-sent events, Electron IPC, or tests."},"443":{"id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import-18","page_id":"/docs/recipes/customer-import","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/customer-import#avoid-one-promise-per-row","content":"That pattern looks tidy until a customer uploads 20,000 rows. Use `mapLimit()` when the input is customer-sized."},"444":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"page","content":"Electron Git Client","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client"},"445":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","content":"An end-to-end shape for a desktop Git app using IPC tuples, abortable subprocesses, and typed renderer calls."},"446":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#main-process-contract","content":"Main-process contract"},"447":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#main-process-implementation","content":"Main-process implementation"},"448":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#preload-bridge","content":"Preload bridge"},"449":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#renderer-usage","content":"Renderer usage"},"450":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#why-this-boundary-feels-cleaner","content":"Why this boundary feels cleaner"},"451":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#good-additions","content":"Good additions"},"452":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#avoid","content":"Avoid"},"453":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","content":"Yieldless fits Electron well because the important boundaries in an Electron app are all failure-heavy: the renderer asks for work through IPC, the main process touches the filesystem, the main process launches long-running child processes like `git clone`."},"454":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#main-process-implementation","content":"If the window is torn down or a parent task group is canceled, the subprocess is aborted through Node's native child-process signal handling."},"455":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#why-this-boundary-feels-cleaner","content":"The renderer never depends on Electron's lossy thrown-error conversion."},"456":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#why-this-boundary-feels-cleaner","content":"The main process can use the same tuple style it uses everywhere else."},"457":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#why-this-boundary-feels-cleaner","content":"Long-running Git subprocesses can be canceled as soon as the UI no longer cares about them."},"458":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-13","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#good-additions","content":"Deduplicate status reads if several panels can request the same repository at once."},"459":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-14","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#good-additions","content":"Wait for one app or window event with cleanup."},"460":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-15","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#avoid","content":"Do not expose arbitrary IPC channels to the renderer."},"461":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-16","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#avoid","content":"Build a small preload bridge with `createIpcBridge()` or `createAbortableIpcBridge()` so the renderer only sees the operations it is allowed to call."},"462":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"page","content":"Electron PR Review Workbench","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench"},"463":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"A practical architecture for a GitHub pull-request review desktop app using tuples in the right places and ordinary UI state in the renderer."},"464":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-contract","content":"Main-process contract"},"465":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"Main-process implementation"},"466":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#preload-bridge","content":"Preload bridge"},"467":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#renderer-state","content":"Renderer state"},"468":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#why-this-fits-pr-review-tools-well","content":"Why this fits PR review tools well"},"469":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#good-additions","content":"Good additions"},"470":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#avoid","content":"Avoid"},"471":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#rule-of-thumb","content":"Rule of thumb"},"472":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"If you are building a GitHub PR review app in Electron, Yieldless fits best in the main process, preload bridge, and service layer. It is less useful as the shape of your React component state."},"473":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"That distinction matters:"},"474":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"Use tuples while you are still doing failure-heavy work: GitHub API calls, local Git reads, diff parsing, cache reads, IPC boundaries."},"475":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"Once the renderer receives the result, fold it into ordinary screen state and move on."},"476":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-13","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"The important thing here is not the exact helper list. It is the layering:"},"477":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-14","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"`yieldless/error` keeps the boundary readable with `ok()` and `err()`."},"478":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-15","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"`yieldless/all` loads the PR payload in parallel."},"479":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-16","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"`yieldless/task` gives the whole request one shared cancellation signal."},"480":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-17","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"`yieldless/node` keeps Git subprocess failures in the same tuple contract."},"481":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-18","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#renderer-state","content":"This is the point where Yieldless should usually stop being the dominant shape."},"482":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-19","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#renderer-state","content":"That keeps the renderer normal. Components render `idle`, `loading`, `ready`, or `error`. They do not need to carry `[error, value]` through every prop."},"483":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-20","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#why-this-fits-pr-review-tools-well","content":"Pull-request work crosses many noisy boundaries: GitHub HTTP, local Git, caches, and Electron IPC."},"484":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-21","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#why-this-fits-pr-review-tools-well","content":"Cancellation matters because users jump between PRs quickly and the old load should stop being important."},"485":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-22","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#why-this-fits-pr-review-tools-well","content":"The renderer wants stable view state, not a low-level transport shape."},"486":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-23","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#good-additions","content":"Deduplicate duplicate PR loads while a user is switching tabs or refreshing panels."},"487":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-24","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#good-additions","content":"Use bounded iterable work when processing many files in a diff."},"488":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-25","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#avoid","content":"Do not keep tuples as your component model."},"489":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-26","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#avoid","content":"Fold the tuple once into `idle`, `loading`, `ready`, and `error` state. UI code should speak in screen states."},"490":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-27","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#rule-of-thumb","content":"Use Yieldless in the main process and preload boundary."},"491":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-28","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#rule-of-thumb","content":"Convert tuples into domain state at the renderer edge."},"492":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-29","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#rule-of-thumb","content":"Do not force tuple results deep into component trees."},"493":{"id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","page_id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","type":"page","content":"Read IDs and Fetch Records","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records"},"494":{"id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","content":"Read IDs from a file, split them line by line, fetch JSON for each ID, and return the accumulated results."},"495":{"id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records#input-file","content":"Input file"},"496":{"id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records#complete-recipe","content":"Complete recipe"},"497":{"id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records#why-foreach-fits","content":"Why forEach fits"},"498":{"id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records#calling-the-recipe","content":"Calling the recipe"},"499":{"id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records#bounded-parallel-version","content":"Bounded parallel version"},"500":{"id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records#common-additions","content":"Common additions"},"501":{"id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","content":"This recipe covers a common first Yieldless workflow:"},"502":{"id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","content":"Read a file with one ID per line."},"503":{"id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","content":"Split and validate the lines."},"504":{"id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","content":"Turn each ID into a number."},"505":{"id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","content":"Use `forEach()` to fetch one record at a time."},"506":{"id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","content":"Accumulate the successful records into an array."},"507":{"id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records-13","page_id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","content":"Use this version when you want sequential requests and the first bad line or failed request should stop the whole job."},"508":{"id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records-14","page_id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records#why-foreach-fits","content":"`forEach()` is sequential. The next ID is not fetched until the current worker returns `[null, undefined]`."},"509":{"id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records-15","page_id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records#why-foreach-fits","content":"That gives you three useful properties:"},"510":{"id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records-16","page_id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records#why-foreach-fits","content":"The returned `customers` array matches the file order."},"511":{"id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records-17","page_id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records#why-foreach-fits","content":"The API receives one request at a time."},"512":{"id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records-18","page_id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records#why-foreach-fits","content":"The first parse, fetch, status, JSON, timeout, or abort error stops the job."},"513":{"id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records-19","page_id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records#why-foreach-fits","content":"The worker receives a scoped `signal`. Pass that signal into real I/O such as `fetchJsonSafe()` so cancellation can do useful work."},"514":{"id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records-20","page_id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records#bounded-parallel-version","content":"When each ID maps to one result and the API can handle a few concurrent requests, `mapAsyncLimit()` is shorter because it collects the output array for you."},"515":{"id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records-21","page_id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records#bounded-parallel-version","content":"`mapAsyncLimit()` still preserves input order in the returned array."},"516":{"id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records-22","page_id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records#common-additions","content":"Add `safeRetry()` inside the worker when one customer fetch can fail transiently:"},"517":{"id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records-23","page_id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records#common-additions","content":"Add `createRateLimiter()` when the remote API has a quota. Create the limiter once outside the loop, then take a slot inside each worker before the fetch:"},"518":{"id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records-24","page_id":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/read-ids-fetch-records#common-additions","content":"Add `createCache()` when repeated IDs should reuse previous successful loads instead of making duplicate HTTP requests."},"519":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"page","content":"Repository Indexer","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer"},"520":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"A larger example that combines queues, pub/sub, caching, batching, limits, retries, task groups, and Node subprocesses."},"521":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#the-indexer","content":"The indexer"},"522":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#using-it-from-a-route-or-action","content":"Using it from a route or action"},"523":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#why-this-is-easier-to-operate","content":"Why this is easier to operate"},"524":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#smaller-variations","content":"Smaller variations"},"525":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#process-a-fixed-list-without-a-long-running-queue","content":"Process a fixed list without a long-running queue"},"526":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#keep-only-the-cache-and-batcher","content":"Keep only the cache and batcher"},"527":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#add-a-circuit-breaker-to-an-optional-dependency","content":"Add a circuit breaker to an optional dependency"},"528":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#avoid-hiding-the-pipeline-inside-a-generic-worker-framework","content":"Avoid: hiding the pipeline inside a generic worker framework"},"529":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"This recipe shows a realistic in-process worker pipeline: a user selects repositories, the app indexes them, progress is streamed to the UI, remote metadata is cached, owner lookups are batched, and local Git subprocesses stay bounded."},"530":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"The point is not to build a new runtime. The point is to keep the moving parts visible:"},"531":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/queue` accepts work with backpressure"},"532":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/pubsub` broadcasts progress"},"533":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-13","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/task` runs workers under one cancellation signal"},"534":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-14","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/limiter` protects API quota and local subprocess capacity"},"535":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-15","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/cache` avoids repeated metadata reads"},"536":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-16","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/batcher` collapses nearby owner lookups"},"537":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-17","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/retry` handles transient remote failures"},"538":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-18","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/fetch` keeps remote calls in tuple form"},"539":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-19","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","content":"`yieldless/node` wraps local Git commands as tuples"},"540":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-20","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#using-it-from-a-route-or-action","content":"In a real UI, the progress subscription often lives in a websocket, server-sent events stream, or Electron IPC handler. The shape stays the same: subscribe, render events, and abort when the user leaves."},"541":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-21","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#why-this-is-easier-to-operate","content":"The queue is bounded, so user-selected work cannot grow memory forever."},"542":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-22","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#why-this-is-easier-to-operate","content":"Worker count is explicit, so local Git subprocesses stay polite."},"543":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-23","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#why-this-is-easier-to-operate","content":"API quota waits happen before remote calls, not after the upstream complains."},"544":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-24","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#why-this-is-easier-to-operate","content":"Metadata reads are cached, but failed reads are not stored."},"545":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-25","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#why-this-is-easier-to-operate","content":"Owner lookups batch together while still returning one result per job."},"546":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-26","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#why-this-is-easier-to-operate","content":"Retry policy sits around the flaky remote read, not around the whole pipeline."},"547":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-27","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#why-this-is-easier-to-operate","content":"Progress is just an async subscription, so it can feed logs, UI, or tests."},"548":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-28","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#process-a-fixed-list-without-a-long-running-queue","content":"If you already have the whole list and do not need progress fanout, `mapLimit()` is smaller."},"549":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-29","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#keep-only-the-cache-and-batcher","content":"If the pipeline is overkill, keep the read model helpers."},"550":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-30","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#add-a-circuit-breaker-to-an-optional-dependency","content":"If indexing can continue without feature flags or recommendations, wrap that optional remote call with a circuit breaker and use a fallback when it is open."},"551":{"id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer-31","page_id":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/repository-indexer#avoid-hiding-the-pipeline-inside-a-generic-worker-framework","content":"That looks shorter, but the operational choices disappear. Yieldless works best when the important limits remain close to the work they protect."},"552":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"page","content":"Resilient Service Flow","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow"},"553":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","content":"A practical backend flow that combines tuples, retries, validation, routing, and cancellation."},"554":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"The moving parts"},"555":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#route-handler","content":"Route handler"},"556":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#why-this-holds-up-well-in-production","content":"Why this holds up well in production"},"557":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#good-variation-add-a-remote-dependency","content":"Good variation: add a remote dependency"},"558":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#avoid-retrying-the-whole-handler","content":"Avoid: retrying the whole handler"},"559":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#rules-worth-keeping","content":"Rules worth keeping"},"560":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","content":"This recipe shows the shape Yieldless is best at: an HTTP request that validates input, performs a few pieces of I/O, retries the flaky part, and returns a normal JSON response."},"561":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/schema` validates input without throwing"},"562":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/fetch` keeps HTTP calls in tuple form"},"563":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/retry` handles transient I/O noise"},"564":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/task` keeps sibling work under one cancellation signal"},"565":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/router` turns tuple results into a plain response"},"566":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-13","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#why-this-holds-up-well-in-production","content":"Validation failures never take the exception path."},"567":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-14","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#why-this-holds-up-well-in-production","content":"If `loadRefs()` fails, `loadStatus()` is aborted immediately."},"568":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-15","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#why-this-holds-up-well-in-production","content":"Retry timers are cancellable because they run through `AbortSignal`."},"569":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-16","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#why-this-holds-up-well-in-production","content":"The handler body stays linear. There is no framework-specific DSL to learn."},"570":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-17","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#good-variation-add-a-remote-dependency","content":"The retry policy is attached to the flaky network call, not to the whole request."},"571":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-18","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#avoid-retrying-the-whole-handler","content":"That repeats validation, routing decisions, and any side effects. Retry the noisy boundary instead."},"572":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-19","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#rules-worth-keeping","content":"Validate early and return early."},"573":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-20","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#rules-worth-keeping","content":"Retry only the noisy boundary, not the entire request."},"574":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-21","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#rules-worth-keeping","content":"Spawn sibling work only when both tasks should die together."},"575":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-22","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#rules-worth-keeping","content":"Map domain misses to explicit HTTP errors like `NotFoundError`."},"576":{"id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","page_id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","type":"page","content":"Simple Recipes","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes"},"577":{"id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","content":"Small Yieldless recipes for one feature at a time."},"578":{"id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes#read-a-text-file","content":"Read a text file"},"579":{"id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes#parse-json-without-throwing","content":"Parse JSON without throwing"},"580":{"id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes#fetch-json-with-a-timeout","content":"Fetch JSON with a timeout"},"581":{"id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes#process-items-one-at-a-time","content":"Process items one at a time"},"582":{"id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes#map-items-with-bounded-concurrency","content":"Map items with bounded concurrency"},"583":{"id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes#retry-one-flaky-call","content":"Retry one flaky call"},"584":{"id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes#cache-a-read-through-lookup","content":"Cache a read-through lookup"},"585":{"id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes#poll-until-a-job-is-ready","content":"Poll until a job is ready"},"586":{"id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes#run-a-command-safely","content":"Run a command safely"},"587":{"id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes#need-a-full-version","content":"Need a full version?"},"588":{"id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","content":"These recipes are intentionally tiny. Each one shows one common task, the module to reach for, and the basic tuple branch you should expect to write."},"589":{"id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","content":"Use these when the larger recipes feel like too much ceremony for the problem in front of you."},"590":{"id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes-13","page_id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes#read-a-text-file","content":"Use this at Node file boundaries where missing files, permissions, or bad paths are normal operational failures."},"591":{"id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes-14","page_id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes#parse-json-without-throwing","content":"Use `safeTrySync()` for sync code that might throw."},"592":{"id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes-15","page_id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes#fetch-json-with-a-timeout","content":"Use this when success means \"the HTTP status was OK and the response body was valid JSON.\""},"593":{"id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes-16","page_id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes#process-items-one-at-a-time","content":"Use `forEach()` when you want order, backpressure, and a stop-on-first-error flow."},"594":{"id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes-17","page_id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes#map-items-with-bounded-concurrency","content":"Use this when each item produces one output and you want more throughput without unbounded `Promise.all()`."},"595":{"id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes-18","page_id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes#retry-one-flaky-call","content":"Retry the unreliable boundary, not the whole business flow."},"596":{"id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes-19","page_id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes#cache-a-read-through-lookup","content":"Successful loads are cached. Failed loads are returned but not stored."},"597":{"id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes-20","page_id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes#poll-until-a-job-is-ready","content":"Use `poll()` when \"not ready yet\" is expected and the caller still needs a firm timeout. `poll()` repeats while the operation returns an error tuple, then stops when it returns `[null, value]`."},"598":{"id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes-21","page_id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes#run-a-command-safely","content":"Use `runCommandSafe(file, args)` when command failure is something your app should display, log, or recover from."},"599":{"id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes-22","page_id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes#need-a-full-version","content":"Beginner Tutorial builds a complete file-to-API workflow step by step."},"600":{"id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes-23","page_id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes#need-a-full-version","content":"Read IDs and Fetch Records is a focused recipe for `readFileSafe()`, `forEach()`, and `fetchJsonSafe()`."},"601":{"id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes-24","page_id":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/simple-recipes#need-a-full-version","content":"Examples has larger compositions once these single-feature recipes feel comfortable."},"602":{"id":"/docs/reference/all","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","type":"page","content":"yieldless/all","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Reference","Reference"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/all"},"603":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-0","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all","content":"Tuple-aware parallel combinators that share cancellation."},"604":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-1","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/all#exports","content":"Exports"},"605":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-2","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/all#example","content":"Example"},"606":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-3","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/all#behavior-notes","content":"Behavior notes"},"607":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-4","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/all#when-to-prefer-runtaskgroup-instead","content":"When to prefer runTaskGroup() instead"},"608":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-5","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/all#good","content":"Good"},"609":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-6","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/all#avoid","content":"Avoid"},"610":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-7","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all","content":"`yieldless/all` gives you helpers for tuple-returning parallel work: `all(tasks)` waits for every task or aborts siblings on the first error, `race(tasks)` resolves with the first settled result and aborts the rest, and `mapLimit(items, mapper, options)` processes a collection with bounded concurrency."},"611":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-8","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#exports","content":"`type SafeTask<T, E = Error> = (signal: AbortSignal) => PromiseLike<SafeResult<T, E>> | SafeResult<T, E>`"},"612":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-9","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#exports","content":"`type MapLimitMapper<Item, Value, E = Error> = (item: Item, index: number, signal: AbortSignal) => PromiseLike<SafeResult<Value, E>> | SafeResult<Value, E>`"},"613":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-10","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#exports","content":"`all(tasks, options): Promise<SafeResult<AllValues<Tasks>, ParallelError<Tasks>>>`"},"614":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-11","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#exports","content":"`mapLimit(items, mapper, { concurrency, signal }): Promise<SafeResult<Value[], E>>`"},"615":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-12","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#exports","content":"`race(tasks, options): Promise<SafeResult<Value, Error>>`"},"616":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-13","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#example","content":"For large batches, use `mapLimit()` to avoid starting every item at once:"},"617":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-14","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#behavior-notes","content":"`all([])` succeeds with an empty array."},"618":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-15","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#behavior-notes","content":"`mapLimit([], mapper, options)` succeeds with an empty array."},"619":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-16","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#behavior-notes","content":"`mapLimit()` preserves input order and throws a `RangeError` when `concurrency` is less than `1` or not an integer."},"620":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-17","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#behavior-notes","content":"`race([])` throws a `RangeError`."},"621":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-18","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#behavior-notes","content":"If any task or mapped item returns `[error, null]`, siblings are aborted before the final tuple is returned."},"622":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-19","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#behavior-notes","content":"`race()` aborts losing tasks immediately, then waits for them to settle before it returns."},"623":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-20","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#behavior-notes","content":"Thrown task and mapper failures are normalized into tuple failures internally."},"624":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-21","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#when-to-prefer-runtaskgroup-instead","content":"Use `all()`, `race()`, and `mapLimit()` when the work is already tuple-native. Use `runTaskGroup()` when you want imperative fan-out and regular promise values."},"625":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-22","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#good","content":"Use `all()` for a small, fixed set of independent tuple tasks."},"626":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-23","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#good","content":"Use `mapLimit()` when a list could be large or expensive."},"627":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-24","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#good","content":"Use `race()` when the first success or first failure should settle the operation."},"628":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-25","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#avoid","content":"Do not pass work that ignores the signal and expect cancellation to be immediate."},"629":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-26","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#avoid","content":"Do not use `all()` for thousands of items. Use `mapLimit()` or `yieldless/iterable` so you can control pressure."},"630":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","type":"page","content":"yieldless/batcher","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Reference","Reference"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/batcher"},"631":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-0","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher","content":"DataLoader-style keyed batching for tuple-returning async reads."},"632":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-1","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/batcher#exports","content":"Exports"},"633":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-2","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/batcher#example","content":"Example"},"634":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-3","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/batcher#behavior-notes","content":"Behavior notes"},"635":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-4","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/batcher#good","content":"Good"},"636":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-5","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/batcher#avoid","content":"Avoid"},"637":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-6","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher","content":"`yieldless/batcher` coalesces nearby `load(key)` calls into one `loadMany(keys, signal)` call. It is useful when many screens, resolvers, or workflow steps can ask for related data in the same tick."},"638":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-7","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher","content":"The module stays intentionally boring: it does not cache, it does not add a scheduler, and it does not require a runtime. It batches pending keys, maps results back by index, and returns tuple results to each caller."},"639":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-8","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher#exports","content":"`createBatcher({ loadMany, waitMs, maxBatchSize }): Batcher`"},"640":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-9","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher#exports","content":"`class MissingBatchResultError extends Error`"},"641":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-10","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher#exports","content":"`type Batcher<Key, Value, E> = { load, clear, pending }`"},"642":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-11","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher#exports","content":"`type BatcherLoadOptions = { signal?: AbortSignal }`"},"643":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-12","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher#behavior-notes","content":"`waitMs` defaults to `0`, which batches calls queued in the same turn."},"644":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-13","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher#behavior-notes","content":"`maxBatchSize` flushes a batch early when enough keys are waiting."},"645":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-14","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher#behavior-notes",